s are even eligible for indexing — an allowlist model, useful precedent for multi-tenant gating.\n\nHermes Agent is architecturally different from what was assumed: `memory_manager.py` is a *provider-orchestration facade* (one built-in + at most one external plugin, e.g. the third-party Hindsight/OpenViking services) — not itself a 3-layer episodic/semantic/procedural store. Hindsight's own taxonomy (raw `world`/`experience` facts vs consolidated, deduplicated `observation` layer) is the closest match to episodic→semantic promotion, but that logic lives in the external service, not Hermes's code. What Hermes does own and do well: recall-time-only sanitization (`sanitize_context`, `StreamingContextScrubber`) that strips injected framing from recalled memory and wraps it in an explicit \"NOT new user input\" system note — a prompt-injection defense applied at read time, with no write-time content scanning; and session lineage via a `parent_session_id` FK chain in SQLite (`hermes_state.py`), used for compression-triggered session splitting.\n\nClaude Code's auto-memory (undocumented at launch, v2.1.32) is the \"one fact, one file\" pattern in its purest form: `~/.claude/projects/<project>/memory/MEMORY.md` index plus per-topic files with SKILL.md-style frontmatter (`name`/`description`/`type`/`originSessionId`), index loaded every session, individual files lazy-`Read`. It has real, documented limits: MEMORY.md is truncated past 200 lines/25KB, and only 5 memories load per query regardless of corpus size — no hybrid vector+keyword fusion at all, purely description-string matching. This is consistent with Anthropic's broader agentic-search bet: the well-corroborated claim that Claude Code dropped an embeddings/vector-DB RAG pipeline for grep/glob/file-read and it \"outperformed everything, by a lot\" (Boris Cherny), later partially validated academically (Amazon Science AAAI'26: agentic keyword search ~94.5% of RAG faithfulness, zero vector store). Counter-evidence exist